Linux is a family of open-source operating systems, which means that the source code is available to the public and can be modified and distributed by anyone. Linux is typically used on servers, desktop computers, and in embedded devices such as smartphones and routers. It is known for being a stable, reliable, and secure operating system, and it is used in a wide variety of applications, including web servers, scientific simulations, and cloud computing. Linux is also popular with programmers and developers because it includes a large number of tools and utilities that make it easy to write, debug, and deploy code.